  abstract = {A simple way to diagnose fractional cloud cover in general circulation\textbackslash nmodels is to relate it to the simulated relative humidity, and allowing\textbackslash nfor fractional cloud cover above a ``critical relative humidity\textbraceleft ''\textbraceright{} of\textbackslash nless than 100\%. In the formulation chosen here, this is equivalent to\textbackslash nassuming a uniform ``top-hat\textbraceleft ''\textbraceright{} distribution of subgrid-scale total\textbackslash nwater content with a variance related to saturation. Critical relative\textbackslash nhumidity has frequently been treated as a ``tunable\textbraceleft ''\textbraceright{} constant, yet it\textbackslash nis an observable. Here, this parameter, and its spatial distribution, is\textbackslash nexamined from Atmospheric Infrared Sounder (AIRS) satellite retrievals,\textbackslash nand from a combination of relative humidity from the ECMWF Re-Analyses\textbackslash n(ERA-Interim) and cloud fraction obtained from CALIPSO lidar satellite\textbackslash ndata. These observational data are used to evaluate results from\textbackslash ndifferent simulations with the ECHAM general circulation model (GCM). In\textbackslash nsensitivity studies, a cloud feedback parameter is analyzed from\textbackslash nsimulations applying the original parameter choice, and applying\textbackslash nparameter choices guided by the satellite data. Model sensitivity\textbackslash nstudies applying parameters adjusted to match the observations show\textbackslash nlarger positive cloud-climate feedbacks, increasing by up to 30\%\textbackslash ncompared to the standard simulation.},
