d pools also play a key role in the organization of\textbackslash nconvection, possibly by their influence on the boundary layer water\textbackslash nvapor field.\textbackslash n\textbackslash n\textbackslash nIn order to see how the water vapor feedback modifies established\textbackslash nconvective organization, a further experiment was conducted with\textbackslash nan SST gradient imposed, which established a mock Walker cell type\textbackslash ncirculation, with ascending motion over the warmest SSTs. After 5\textbackslash ndays, the SST gradient is reversed to see how the convection would\textbackslash nestablish itself over the new SST maximum. This highly idealized\textbackslash nexperiment therefore represents a surrogate for the atmospheric response\textbackslash nto SST ``hotspots,'' that observations have shown to form under the\textbackslash ndescending branch of large-scale tropical circulations such as the\textbackslash nMadden--Jullian oscillation, due to increased incident solar radiation\textbackslash nand decreased latent heat fluxes at the surface. It is found that\textbackslash nthe convection does not spontaneously initiate over the new SST maximum,\textbackslash nbut instead must propagate toward it. After a further 5 days, much\textbackslash nlonger than the boundary layer adjustment timescale, the warmest\textbackslash nSSTs are still completely free from convection. This is directly\textbackslash ndue to the dryness of the atmosphere caused by the initial period\textbackslash nof subsidence.\textbackslash n\textbackslash n\textbackslash nA further set of experiments examines the robustness of the feedback\textbackslash nin cases of imposed vertical wind shear. It is found that strong\textbackslash nwind shears prevent the feedback by effectively mixing water vapor.\textbackslash nHowever, the feedback is still very important in cases of weak wind\textbackslash nshears.},
